03757nmm a2200553Ia 9781501734533DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20191991nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017345337 a10.7591/97815017345332doi  a(DE-B1597)534423  a(OCoLC)1129186084  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a823/.7qOCoLC220/eng/202302161 aFerris, Ina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Achievement of Literary Authority :bGender, History, and the Waverly Novels /cIna Ferris. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough literary historians have largely neglected them, Sir Walter Scott's Waverley Novels mark a pivotal moment in the formation of the modern literary field, Ina Ferris argues, exemplifying the complex intersections of gender and genre in the evolution of nineteenth-century literary authority. Focusing on the critical reception of Scott's early works, Ferris shows how their extraordinary success propelled the novel from the margins of the culture into the literary hierarchy.Drawing on the insights of poststructuralist, feminist, and Bakhtinian theory, Ferris reconstructs reviewers' debates about fiction at several critical points in Scott's career. His literary authority and innovative power, she maintains, depended on the way in which his historical novels responded to the anxieties about discourse and modernity expressed in the literary reviews. Gender was a central source of anxiety, and the "manliness" of Scott's historical novels was decisive in their legitimation of the novel. It was largely through a problematic allegiance to the "female" genre of romance, however, that the Waverley Novels both recuperated fiction for male reading and helped to redefine for the nineteenth century the writing of history itself. Ferris locates the Waverley Novels in relation to fiction and history by such contemporaries of Scott's as Maria Edgeworth, Lady Morgan, John Galt, James Hogg, Augustin Thierry, and Thomas Babington Macaulay.Students of the novel, feminist critics, and others interested in the relations between history and fiction will want to read The Achievement of Literary Authority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthority in literature. 0aAuthorshipxSex differences. 0aHistorical fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 4aGender Studies. 4aLiterary Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173453340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501734533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501734533/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles